# AGENTS.md

## Project

`{{ project_name }}` is a small Python service generated from `python-service-scaffold`.

The codebase is organized around explicit building blocks:

- `runtimes` for ways to run the service
- `features` for business capabilities
- `infra` for technical adapters and shared infrastructure
- `models` for shared business models
- `protocols` for cross-layer interfaces

Keep the structure small and predictable. Prefer placing code into an existing package over creating new top-level directories.

## Placement rules

When adding or changing code, use these rules first:

- Put runtime entrypoints, request/response wiring, and transport-specific adapters in `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/`.
- Put business use cases and feature-specific contracts in `{{ package_name }}/features/`.
- Put shared domain models used by multiple features or runtimes in `{{ package_name }}/models/`.
- Put infrastructure adapters and technical wiring in `{{ package_name }}/infra/`.
- Put interfaces between business code and infrastructure in `{{ package_name }}/protocols/`.
- Put tests in `tests/`, close to the behavior they verify.
- Put project-wide operational notes in `README.md`, not inside package modules.

## Concretely, store things here

- New CLI commands or startup wiring: `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/cli/`
- New HTTP routers, dependencies, schemas, lifecycle hooks, and middleware: `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/http/`
- New Telegram bot routers, callbacks, keyboards, FSM states, and dispatcher wiring: `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/tg_bot/`
- New FastStream brokers, subscribers, publishers, and stream runtime wiring: `{{ package_name }}/runtimes/stream/`
- Feature business flows: `{{ package_name }}/features/<feature_name>/use_cases/`
- Feature-specific ports or contracts: `{{ package_name }}/features/<feature_name>/`
- If a feature accumulates too many contracts, split `contracts.py` into `{{ package_name }}/features/<feature_name>/contracts/` instead of keeping one large module.
- Feature-specific infrastructure that should stay close to the feature: `{{ package_name }}/features/<feature_name>/infra/`
- Shared settings and config models: `{{ package_name }}/settings.py`
- Shared logging setup: `{{ package_name }}/infra/logging/`
- Redis clients and Redis-specific integration helpers: `{{ package_name }}/infra/redis/`
- Database session management and unit-of-work code: `{{ package_name }}/infra/db/`
- SQLAlchemy database models: `{{ package_name }}/infra/db/models/`
- Database migrations: `alembic/`

## Boundaries

- Do not put business logic into runtime modules when it can live in a feature use case.
- Do not put HTTP-specific or CLI-specific code into `features/`.
- Do not make `features/` depend directly on FastAPI, FastStream, Click, SQLAlchemy sessions, or other runtime details when a port or protocol is enough.
- Do not add hidden framework layers or generic base abstractions unless the codebase already needs them in multiple places.
- Do not create a new top-level package for a concern that fits under `runtimes`, `features`, `infra`, `models`, or `protocols`.

## Examples

- Complex feature example: an `orders` feature can live under `{{ package_name }}/features/orders/` with `use_cases/create_order.py`, `use_cases/cancel_order.py`, `use_cases/get_order.py`, feature contracts or ports in the package root, and persistence adapters in `{{ package_name }}/features/orders/infra/`.
- Workflow-heavy feature example: a `billing` or `subscriptions` feature should keep orchestration and business rules in `{{ package_name }}/features/<feature_name>/use_cases/`, expose only feature-level contracts to runtimes, and keep payment-provider or storage adapters outside the runtime layer.
- Shared model example: if `orders`, `billing`, and HTTP pagination all need the same business entity or page result, place the shared type in `{{ package_name }}/models/` instead of redefining it inside each feature or runtime schema package.
- Integration example: if `orders` needs persistence, keep database session handling in `{{ package_name }}/infra/db/`, keep ORM models in `{{ package_name }}/infra/db/models/`, and keep order-specific mapping or repository code near the feature or in explicit infrastructure adapters.

## Working style

- Keep generated code easy to delete, replace, or simplify.
- Prefer explicit wiring over magic.
- Keep optional integrations isolated so they can be removed without rewriting unrelated business code.
- If a change is runtime-specific, keep it inside that runtime package.
- If a change is business-specific, prefer a feature package even if only one runtime uses it today.

## Common commands

- Run locally: `make run`
- Run tests: `make test`
